        <mxCell id="TxqwB5bRfBVEWZzc2l-F-157" parent="1" style="text;whiteSpace=wrap;fontSize=16;spacing=1.9684999999999997;spacingTop=-3.9369999999999994;" value="1. Functional Requirements (FRs)&#xa;Search &amp; Discovery:&#xa;The system should allow users to search events using parameters like title, location, or category, supporting fuzzy matching for better results.&#xa;Seat Selection:&#xa;Users must be able to view seat layouts in real-time along with current availability.&#xa;Temporary Seat Reservation:&#xa;Selected seats should be locked atomically for a short duration (e.g., 5 minutes) to avoid concurrent booking conflicts.&#xa;Booking &amp; Payment:&#xa;The platform should handle secure payment processing and automatically generate tickets upon successful transactions.&#xa;Asynchronous Notifications:&#xa;Users should receive booking confirmations via Email/SMS after the transaction is completed.&#xa;&#xa; 2. Non-Functional Requirements (NFRs)&#xa;High Availability:&#xa;The system, especially search and browsing, should maintain an uptime of at least 99.99%.&#xa;Strong Consistency:&#xa;Seat allocation and booking operations must ensure strict consistency to eliminate double bookings.&#xa;Low Latency:&#xa;Search responses should be delivered within ~100ms, and seat locking operations within ~200ms.&#xa;Scalability:&#xa;The system must handle sudden spikes in traffic (100k+ requests per second), especially during popular releases.&#xa;Fault Tolerance:&#xa;External dependencies like payment gateways should be protected using circuit breakers to avoid cascading failures.&#xa;&#xa;3. API Design&#xa;GET /v1/events?city={id}&amp;q={query}&#xa;Retrieves event listings filtered using ElasticSearch.&#xa;GET /v1/shows/{show_id}/seats&#xa;Returns the current seat layout and availability using cache/read replicas.&#xa;POST /v1/seats/lock&#xa;(Payload: seat_ids[])&#xa;Locks selected seats using Redis (SETNX) with a TTL of 300 seconds.&#xa;POST /v1/bookings&#xa;Creates a booking entry in pending state and initiates payment processing.&#xa;POST /v1/payments/webhook&#xa;Handles asynchronous callbacks from the payment gateway to confirm transaction status.&#xa;&#xa; 4. Core Entities&#xa;User:&#xa;Contains user profile information, authentication details, and preferences.&#xa;Event / Show:&#xa;Includes event metadata such as venue, timing, and associated details.&#xa;Seat:&#xa;Represents individual seat information including position, category (e.g., VIP, Gold), and pricing.&#xa;Booking / Order:&#xa;Stores transaction details linking user, show, and selected seats.&#xa;SeatLock:&#xa;Represents temporary seat reservations managed via Redis.&#xa;&#xa; 5. Database Schema Design&#xa;User Table:&#xa;(user_id, name, email, phone)&#xa;Show Table:&#xa;(show_id, event_id, venue_id, start_time, base_price)&#xa;Seat Table:&#xa;(seat_id, show_id, seat_number, status [Available, Locked, Booked])&#xa;Booking Table:&#xa;(booking_id, user_id, show_id, total_amount, status [Pending, Paid, Failed])&#xa;Outbox Table:&#xa;(event_id, payload, status)&#xa;Used to implement the Transactional Outbox Pattern for reliable event publishing to Kafka.&#xa;&#xa; 6. High-Level Design (HLD)&#xa;&#xa;The system is designed using a microservices architecture optimized for high concurrency and scalability:&#xa;&#xa;Edge Layer:&#xa;A CDN is used for delivering static assets efficiently, while a Layer 7 Load Balancer distributes incoming requests across API Gateways.&#xa;Concurrency Management:&#xa;Redis-based distributed locking (SETNX with TTL) is used to temporarily reserve seats. Locks automatically expire after 5 minutes or are released on payment failure.&#xa;Search Architecture:&#xa;A Change Data Capture (CDC) mechanism streams database updates to ElasticSearch via Kafka Connect, enabling near real-time search capabilities.&#xa;Reliability Strategy:&#xa;The Transactional Outbox Pattern ensures consistency between database updates and Kafka event publishing, keeping downstream services (like notifications) in sync.&#xa;Data Access Pattern:&#xa;Write-heavy operations (like bookings) are handled by the primary SQL database, while read-heavy operations (like seat maps) are served through read replicas or caching layers." vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="800" width="911.67" x="315" y="-1289" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
